\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MonkeyBars Reaper Scripts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The URL to import in ReaPack is https://github.com/MonkeyBars3k/ReaScripts/raw/master/index.xml.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Glue (Reversible)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Background\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two main ways to consolidate selected items on a track in Reaper: {\b Glue} and {\b Groups}. Both have disadvantages.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Glue} is permanent: once you glue items together, you cannot make edits later without cutting again. This has disadvantages, as you may wish to extend the length of one of the enclosed items (such as make the sound of a kick drum's tail longer, etc.). You cannot do this using Glue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The other option is to {\b Group} items. This works well if you simply want to move items around or select multiple items by clicking one item; however, you cannot use the other benefits of Reaper items, such as quickly looping, take envelopes, etc. Grouping can become confusing because Groups are highlighted in green around the items, but {\i not} around the boundary of the group itself. Groups can be unwieldy to work with in many musical contexts, such as a four-bar repetition. Groups tend to create visual clutter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Glue (Reversible)} aims to address the shortcomings of both Glue and Groups, as well as restore the convenient functionality already present in items (looping, timestretching, and much more), by placing selected items in a new container item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 How to use\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b To use Glue (Reversible)}, simply select items or make a time selection with items inside and trigger the Glue (Reversible) script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To edit your glued items, {\b Unglue (Reversible)} opens the created container item; the items inside are automatically grouped for you. You can see the container item created with Glue (Reversible), but the items inside are now visible and directly editable. Continue working with them as grouped items and/or reglue them again with Glue (Reversible).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can Glue (Reversible) existing container items, nondestructively {\b nesting} container items. There is no limit in the code as to how many times you can nest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Features\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fills in the missing {\b nondestructive/reversible Glue function} in Reaper!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \endash \tx360\tab A.k.a.: Glue Groups, Item Containers, Container Items, Pooled Item Boxes\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Currently, Glue (Reversible) container item copies are {\b pooled by default}. Editing and regluing one container item {\b updates all instances}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \endash \tx360\tab Considering Reaper is missing native Pooled Audio Items, this is great! However, we do plan to allow this to be toggled off and back on with a global script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Supports {\b nesting Glue (Reversible) container items} inside other container items! When you update the nested container item, the script checks the parent item and updates that as well. Tested with 20 levels of nesting.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Notes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Requires {\b SWS Plugin Extension}, of course!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When you {\b Unglue (Reversible)}, a new empty item "grc" is inserted under the original items. This item has the data to recall which group these items came from \u8211- don't delete it unless you want to glue the items and make a new, unpooled group that doesnt update other instances.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If you want to {\b move items} inside an unglued container, you'll need to ungroup them temporarily. When you regroup them, ensure that you select ALL the items in the group so the script can keep track of the container and update all the pooled instances after reglue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If you {\b add new items} to a Glue (Reversible) container item, select them AND at least one of the original items to make sure they get added to the existing container item. If you only tweak the existing items, you can select any item and reglue, and the script will remember which container item it belongs to.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can use the {\b empty container} "grc" to create silence at the start and end of the glued wav.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Uses item notes/names to keep track of which container item items belong in. If you see "gr:1" or "grc:1", {\b don't delete it from the item's name}, as the code depends on that name to find it! You can add text to notes/names AFTER \u8211- e.g. "gr:1 - My extra text"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To create {\b MIDI container items}, the script uses "Apply track FX as new take" on each item to get a (silent) wav audio take. When you Unglue (Reversible), the wav take is removed and just the original MIDI take is restored to active. Currently only MIDI on virtual instrument tracks is supported.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When using copies of Glue (Reversible) container items, you can't make a copy of itself inside itself, as that would cause an infinite recursion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Uses selection set slot 10 at times to save and recall selected items.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 History\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 matthewjumpsoffbuildings created the powerful, excellent "Glue Groups" scripts: https://bitbucket.org/matthewjumpsoffbuildings/reaper-scripts/src/master/\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MonkeyBars continues the effort with some different nomenclature (in the interest of onboarding new users and making it easy to find in the Actions Window), bugfixes, and additional features.\par}
